John Edward: Language Skills Essential to World Citizens
The independent schools in Scotland have an excellent state of service in the field of academic excellence, and this has continued in 2018 with again an excellent series of exam results, as well as individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other initiatives across the community.
With more than 30,000 students in Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further and higher education, the career they choose and their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made school curriculum, we see that modern languages are popular and desired subjects remain excellent within schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “When you talk to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
When you talk to him in his own language, you reach his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s recent exam results we can deduce that languages are at the top of the ranking, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of the students who studied foreign languages achieved a high score.
The data, collected from 74 schools affiliated with SCIS, shows that 72 per cent of students achieved a high score (‘A’) in Mandarin, while 72 per cent of German students, 69 per cent of French students and 63 per cent of Spanish students also achieved an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now considered as subjects as equally valued as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school programs and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission found that 17 percent of the obstacles to filling jobs were attributed to a lack of language skills, according to employers.
Language skills are thus becoming increasingly important to prepare young people for their future careers.
As more and more jobs require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he has a real advantage in the future with such a skill for life.
Direct communication with people from abroad automatically gives a multilingual person an advantage over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation. French was the only language that came out above 10 percent, with a total of 15 percent.
This is why investing in language education is now important for today’s children.
Multiple languages, especially those of emerging economies, will give children a better chance of finding a meaningful job.
In Scotland, schools choose which languages they teach themselves.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other schools will teach languages that are most important for the UK when they look forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers specializing in this field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills needed to succeed, regardless of the future.
Currently, it cannot be denied that languages in a global business environment remain vital for the future of the country, so this needs to be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be regarded as 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
