Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit between an active US president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim promised to work on the “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula,” while Trump ordered no-looking guarantees for the vegetation.
North Korea is aiming for a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed calls for a tightening of international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States is pushing for ‘denuclearization first’ and increasing pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal in a compelling way and even by objecting to the ‘declaration of the end of war’,” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can put us on our knees is an air castle of people who are unaware of us.
