Harvard students take a course on the importance of sufficient rest
A new course at Harvard University this year ensures that all students get more sleep, in an effort to fight the growing macho culture in which it seems cool to study all night and drink a lot of caffeine.
A professor found that students at the world’s largest university often have no idea of the basic principles of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School, a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, set up the course. As far as he knows, this is unique in the United States.
He got the idea to start the course after giving a speech about the influence of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end of my speech, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why am I just getting to hear this now, in my last year?’
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is organized for the first time this year, explains to students the basic principles of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance and how they also promote their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to organize the course when it was found that students had a severe sleep deficiency during the week.
The course lasts one hour and includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one of the parts, the students see an image of a bedroom, where they click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise appliances and books to learn more about the effects of caffeine and light and how sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
Using a map of the campus, with interactive pictograms, participants are encouraged to think about their daily routine.
“We know that we will not immediately change the behavior of the students.
But we find that they have the right to know all this, just as people have the right to know the consequences of choosing cigarettes on their health, Ceisler added.
The culture of pride on a night of study still exists, he says, and due to modern technology and increasing pressure on students, sleep deprivation is an ever-increasing problem.
Ensuring enough sleep, of good quality, should be the student’s ‘secret weapon’ to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deficiency causes the brain to give them a constant feeling of hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from California who studied chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to set up the course, after which he had attended the professor's lesson last year when he was studying at Harvard in his first year.
He said the course had opened his eyes and had inspired him to make sure the course became available to everyone on campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all students to follow a similar curriculum before they come to the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm for their bedtime, and not just an alarm to stand up. They should also be aware of the harmful effects of the ‘blue light’ of electronic screens and LED lighting, which can derail your circadian rhythm, causing you to have trouble sleeping in.
