HIV/AIDS: China reports a 14% increase in new cases
China says the number of Chinese people living with HIV and AIDS has increased by 14%.
Health authorities say that more than 820.000 people have been affected in the country.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, 40,000 new cases were reported.
In the vast majority of new cases, the diseases were transmitted through sex, which was previously not the case.
In the past, HIV has spread rapidly in some parts of China through transfusions of infected blood.
But the number of people who get HIV in this way is now near zero, Chinese health officials said at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, compared to the same period last year, the number of people with HIV and AIDS in China increased by 100,000.
The transmission of HIV through sex is an acute problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality is no longer a crime in China since 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is said to be widespread.
Because of the country’s conservative values, studies estimate that 70 to 90% of men who have sex with men will eventually marry a woman.
Often the diseases are transmitted by insufficient protection in sexual relations in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to HIV medicine as part of its efforts to address the problem.
