Earthquakes and tsunami in Indonesia
At least 384 people have been killed by a powerful earthquake and tsunami that struck the Indonesian city of Palu on Friday, officials said, and the death toll is expected to continue to rise.
Due to the shutdown of the means of communication, the official authorities have not yet received information from the regency of Donggala, an area north of Palu that is closer to the epicenter of the earthquake with a force of 7.5 on the Richter scale.
In Palu, more than 16,000 people have been evacuated after the disaster occurred.
Here are some important facts about Palu and Dongala, on the island of Celebes:
Palu is the capital of the province of Midden-Celebes and is located at the end of a narrow bay on the west coast of the island of Celebes, with an estimated population of 379,800 in 2017.
The city celebrated its 40th birthday when the tsunami struck.
Dongala is a regency that extends over more than 300 km along the coast of northwest Celebes.
The regency, an administrative region just below a province, had an estimated population of 299,200 in 2017.
Fisheries and agriculture are the main activities in the economy of the province of Middle Celebes, especially in the coastal region of Donggala.
Nickel mines are also important in the province, but they are mostly located in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Celebes.
Palu and Donggala have been affected by tsunamis regularly over the past 100 years, according to the Indonesian Disaster Control Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami claimed more than 200 lives and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
A tsunami also struck in western Donggala in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located on the Pacific Ring of Fire and is often affected by earthquakes.
Here is a list of some of the worst earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A major earthquake on the west coast of Indonesian province of Atjeh in northern Sumatra on December 26 caused a tsunami that hit 14 countries and claimed a total of 226,000 lives along the coasts of the Indian Ocean, more than half of which in Atjeh.
2005: A series of severe earthquakes occurred on the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds of people were killed on the island of Nias, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: An earthquake with a magnitude of 6.8 on the Richter scale occurred south of Java, Indonesia's most densely populated island, and caused a tsunami that hit the south coast and claimed nearly 700 lives.
2009: An earthquake with a magnitude of 7.6 on the Richter scale hit the city of Padang, the capital of the West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: An earthquake with a magnitude of 7.5 on the Richter scale hit one of the Mentawai islands off the coast of Sumatra, causing a tsunami of more than 10 meters that destroyed dozens of villages and claimed about 300 lives.
2016: An opaque earthquake hit the Pidie rainforest in Atjeh and caused devastation and panic, as people were reminded of the devastations of the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
There was no tsunami this time, but more than 100 people were killed by collapsed buildings.
2018: Several earthquakes hit the Indonesian tourist island of Lombok, killing more than 500 people, mostly on the northern side of the island.
